Depends a lot on the actual musical context and on the amp's speaker
setup.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I would assume to tell the guitar players to turn down the bass settings
&gt; on their amps and even on the bass amp.
">

I wouldn't, but I would ask them to avoid turning it up. Basically if
their rigs do not sound OK as they are, they need fixing.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; With drums unmiked they would be in competition for the low frequencies
&gt; with the guitars and bass.
">

I doubt that and would rather say &quot;not to worry&quot;, you won't get the body
feel of rock at sane sound levels if your start curtailing the naturally
occuring bass level.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Any comments on a good live eq mix onstage?
">

Do nothing is a good default eq strategy. But there are very different
cases to consider, such as also whether guitar and bass plays parts of
the same chord or whether they are in dialogue. Some of the time they
should blend to one instrument.

Not having them amplified via a PA adds the option of solid directional
clues because you hear them from each their instrument, I consider amp
and loudspeaker to be integral parts of the instruments in question.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Assume that it's not that the guitar players are too loud- just eq
&gt; settings on individual amps.
">

OK, will try assume, but you do realize that what you ask for is very
difficult? - guitar players are notoriously difficult to control, they
always have an extra volume control somewhere ...

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; cull ... @rogers.com
">

Kind regards

Peter Larsen
