This is great advice, but sometimes hard to put into practice.  In my
experience, the drummer sets the stage volume; everything else
(guitars, vocal monitors, etc.) have to be up high enough to be heard
over the crash cymbals and snares.  Particular the lead guitarist
(e.g., me) needs to be able to hear himself well enough not to get
lost while soloing, and the guitar (as well as vocals) shares much of
the frequency space with cymbals and snare.

There are drummers who can drum well with a light touch (and light
sticks) and drummers who can't.  The latter seem to be more common.
I've seen the trick of putting up a plexiglass shield around the
drummmer, and it makes a lot of sense, but we don't have one yet (I'm
not even sure where to get one or what it would cost).
