As the lead guitarist (and backing vocalist) in my band, I've taking
to putting my Fender combo on a tilt-back stand right next to my wedge
monitor, facing backwards and up toward (but slightly behind) my
head.    That way, I hear less of my guitar when I'm at the mic
singing, more when I step back to play a solo.  The FOH gets all of my
guitar via the PA.  It works well because I can keep the overall amp
volume way down and still hear it over the drums and everything else,
it doesn't bleed much into my vocal mic (because it's behind the mic),
and the drummer can hear me well enough to know where I am in my
solos.  The other guys get a little of my guitar in their monitors, if
they need it (e.g., on an open stage with no reflecting wall behind
us)

Interestingly, I've had at least two sound guys tell me that they had
never seen a guitarist set up their amp like that. Then, after a
pause, they said &quot;seems like a great idea!&quot;

As for Fender &quot;toob&quot; tone, I have found that no matter how large the
venue, the guy running sound always begs me to keep the amp down to
around 3-4, which means it's basically running clean.  Therefore I get
all of my tone from pedals.  No one in the audience has ever
complained that my tone is from the pedals not the power tubes.
